Done. Fresh-eyes notes added to the bottom of `src/blog/people/drafts/Nick-Offerman.md`.

**What I reviewed:** the full Nick Offerman Type 9 draft, with a quick reality check against his recent public work.

**The two biggest issues I flagged:**

1. **The Last of Us is buried.** Offerman's Emmy-winning turn as Bill in "Long, Long Time" (2023) — a gruff survivalist loner who falls into a tender 20-year love story — is the strongest possible proof of this draft's entire thesis (the softie behind the mustache, the inversion of Ron Swanson). It currently appears only as one clause in the rabbit-hole counterargument. It should anchor a real body beat, ideally right after the "Why Nick Offerman isn't Ron Swanson" section.

2. **The "merging / dissolve / separate wanting self" motif is overused** — it fires in five-plus sections, so the reader starts noticing the framework instead of the man before the (otherwise strong) ending lands.

I also noted a duplicate quote (the "jackass like me" line appears in prose *and* as the pull-quote right below it), the "I negotiate with hugging" line running three times, and an underused "author" dimension despite the frontmatter tag. No body edits made, per the command.

